2 Orientation to statistical graphics

2.1 Discussion

There are three main ways you can produce graphics in R. In order of inception, they are

  • base R
  • lattice (an R package)
  • ggplot2 (an R package)
    • Part of the tidyverse

Why ggplot2?

  • once fluent, can make most plots up to publication quality standard very quickly.
  • has theoretical underpinning in the “layered grammar of graphics”, which is described in the book by Leland Wilkinson.

Stackoverflow was my main source of learning. Google what you’re trying to do, and persevere. You can do it.

Jenny Bryan on statistical graphics:

  • A picture is worth 1000 words
  • More philosophy on graphics
  • Comparing base R/lattice/ggplot2
  • The learning curve

3 The grammar of graphics

  • is based off of the grammar of graphics (book by Leland Wilkinson) – hence “gg”.
  • layer-based

3.1 Learning Objectives

3.2 Discussion

Here are the seven grammar of graphics components, where the bold ones are necessary to specify for every plot:

  • Data
  • Aesthetic mappings
  • Geometric objects
  • Scales
  • Statistical transformations
  • Coordinate system
  • Facet specification

Examples:

  1. Scatterplot: gdpPercap vs. lifeExp:

  • aesthetic mapping: x and y
  • geometric object: points
  • scale: linear
  • statistical transformation: none
  • coordinate system: rectangular
  • facetting: none
  1. Boxplot: continent vs lifeExp

  • aesthetic mapping: x and y
  • geometric object: boxplot
  • scale: linear
  • statistical transformation: quartiles and whiskers
  • coordinate system: rectangular
  • facetting: none
  1. Line plot: year vs pop for Canada

  • aesthetic mapping: x and y
  • geometric object: lines
  • scale: linear
  • statistical transformation: none
  • coordinate system: rectangular
  • facetting: none

4 Plotting with x and y aesthetics

4.1 Learning Objectives

Our objective is to explore the various plot types by:

  • using the x and y aesthetic mappings, while
  • using different geometric objects.

By the end of this lesson, students are expected to be able to:

  • create data visualizations for the following situations:
    • two numeric variables
    • one numeric, one categorical variable
    • one numeric variable
